<!-- HOOD TYPES -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Hood Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every range hood configuration in LA kitchens</h2>
    <p class="lead">Mounting style, venting type, and brand all affect how we diagnose and access the unit. We come prepared for each configuration.</p>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Under-Cabinet</div>
        <h3>Under-Cabinet Hoods</h3>
        <p>Most common in standard kitchens and apartments. Mounted beneath upper cabinets. Usually vented through the cabinet above or directly through the wall. Common in LA's older housing stock and renovated condos.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Wall-Mounted</div>
        <h3>Wall-Mounted Chimney Hoods</h3>
        <p>Decorative stainless or custom-panel chimney hoods mounted on the wall above the range. Popular in renovated kitchens across Westside LA. Higher-end models from Zephyr, Vent-A-Hood, Hestan, and Wolf.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Island</div>
        <h3>Island / Ceiling Hoods</h3>
        <p>Suspended from the ceiling over an island or peninsula cooktop. Require ceiling duct routing. Common in open-plan LA kitchens with island cooktops. Generally higher CFM requirements than wall-mounted units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Insert</div>
        <h3>Insert / Built-In Hoods</h3>
        <p>The ventilation unit is concealed inside custom cabinetry — only the grille and controls are visible. Common in high-end kitchens where the hood is integrated into the cabinetry design. Brands: Wolf, Miele, Thermador, Best.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Vented</div>
        <h3>Vented (Ducted) Hoods</h3>
        <p>Exhausts air to the exterior through ductwork. Far more effective than recirculating — removes smoke, moisture, heat, and odors entirely. Required for high-BTU professional ranges. The correct choice for serious cooking.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Ventless</div>
        <h3>Ventless / Recirculating Hoods</h3>
        <p>Filters air through grease and charcoal filters, then returns it to the kitchen. The only option in many apartments without duct access. Charcoal filters must be replaced every 3–6 months — not cleanable. We carry replacements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Fan Not Working / No Suction</h3>
        <p>Check the grease filter first — a saturated filter can reduce airflow dramatically. If the filter is clean and the fan still doesn't pull air, the fan motor has failed. On multi-speed hoods, individual speed settings can fail independently — one speed works, others don't.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Loud Rattling or Vibration</h3>
        <p>A blower wheel caked with grease becomes unbalanced and vibrates the entire hood. Cleaning the blower wheel — a separate component from the motor — often resolves the noise without replacing anything. If noise persists after cleaning, the motor bearings are failing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Grinding or Squealing Noise</h3>
        <p>Fan motor bearing failure. The motor continues to run but with increasing noise as the bearings degrade. Left unaddressed, the motor eventually seizes. We carry replacement motors for the major brands we service most in LA.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Lights Not Working</h3>
        <p>Usually a burned-out bulb, a failed light socket, or a loose wiring connection. On LED range hoods with integrated lighting, the LED board itself can fail. We carry replacement bulbs and sockets for the common brands. LED board replacement on premium hoods requires sourcing OEM components.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Control Panel / Buttons Not Responding</h3>
        <p>A failed control board or a membrane switch panel that's degraded. On touchscreen hoods (Zephyr, Broan Elite), the capacitive touch layer can fail. We test the switch panel and wiring before recommending a full board replacement, which is more expensive.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Hood Completely Dead</h3>
        <p>Check the circuit breaker first — range hoods are often on a dedicated circuit. A blown thermal fuse inside the hood (triggered by excessive grease buildup causing heat) can also cut all power. A completely dead hood on an intact circuit usually has a failed control board or power supply component.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- CFM / PRO RANGE SPOTLIGHT -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Pro Ranges &amp; CFM</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why your hood may not be broken — it may just be undersized</h2>
    <p class="lead">LA has more professional-grade ranges per home than almost any other city. This creates a specific situation most repair companies don't address: the hood is working but it was never adequate for the range beneath it.</p>

    <div class="cfm-block">
      <div class="cfm-label">🔥 High-BTU Ranges &amp; Ventilation</div>
      <h3>A Wolf range at 60,000 BTU needs a very different hood than a standard range</h3>
      <p>Standard residential range hoods are typically rated at 400–600 CFM. A Wolf, Thermador, or BlueStar professional range with six burners running full can generate 30,000–60,000+ BTU of heat and combustion byproducts. The general rule of thumb is 100 CFM per 10,000 BTU — meaning a 60,000 BTU range needs 600 CFM at minimum, and ideally more when accounting for duct resistance and filter restriction.</p>
      <p>Many LA homes have premium pro ranges installed under standard consumer hoods — either because the kitchen was renovated incrementally, or because the hood was selected for aesthetics rather than performance. When a homeowner calls us saying their range hood "doesn't work" over their Wolf, the first question we ask is what CFM the hood is rated for versus what the range requires. If the hood is mechanically sound but undersized, that's honest information worth having before spending money on parts that won't solve the problem.</p>

      <div class="cfm-grid">
        <div class="cfm-item"><strong>Standard range (30K BTU)</strong><span>300 CFM minimum — standard residential hoods usually adequate</span></div>
        <div class="cfm-item"><strong>Pro range (60K BTU)</strong><span>600 CFM minimum — most consumer hoods are undersized for this</span></div>
